final_thought: The water feels like bathwater now, even at dawn. The tourists still
  come, but they're here to see what's left before it's all gone. I'm documenting
  the death of everything I've spent my life trying to save.
last_days_scenario: Maria floats above the bleached skeleton of what was once Mesoamerica's
  largest coral formation, her dive computer showing 31.2°C - a temperature that would
  have been an emergency just five years ago, now routine. The few remaining coral
  colonies are stark white, their symbiotic algae expelled in a desperate fever response
  that never ends. Her underwater camera captures the dissolution - literally, as
  increasing ocean acidity eats away at the calcium carbonate structures built over
  centuries. The last dive shop on the island closed yesterday. The desalination plant
  that kept the resort running failed when algal blooms clogged its intake filters.
  Maria checks her temperature logger one final time, watching the numbers climb past
  any threshold for recovery. Like the colonial coral polyps that built these reefs
  over generations, she cannot survive alone when the entire system collapses. The
  fever dreams started three days ago when the air conditioning failed and the heat
  became inescapable, even underwater.
